tweet: Any amount of shuffling or not shuffling is having an effect on the deck you are presenting. As @clentdc said, When sideboarding do you place the cards on top or bottom and then thoroughly shuffling or are you spacing them out randomly throughout the library before shuffling?

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: Reduce, not remove. How many times have you had an enjoyable game of magic where you or your opponent drew all or no lands/didn't make any relevant plays (without you or them playing chalice).

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: If we're going to say "that's just part of the game, sometimes you get flooded or you get mana screwed" but never in the history of magic has anyone had an enjoyable game of magic drawing all or no lands. SHOULD we seek to eliminate this point of variance or just play hearthstone

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: I hear what you are saying. We also build our decks to reduce variance. This new mulligan rule is rumored to be to reduce variance. Many newer games are removing resources from the deck for the nongames it can lead to. /1

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: Maybe its a peace of mind thing knowing that at least at one point the lands were spread out and if by virtue of randomness lands clump during shuffling then so be it. But being a poor shuffler and getting 75% of the lands on top of the library results in nongames.

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: How many times after playing g1 & you get a mana pocket to start g2. The term mana pocket exists because it happens. To unclump lands thereby reducing that variance & then shuffling sufficiently randomizes while still reducing variance. How many ppl make perfect riffle shuffles?

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: After listening to some pods this week discussing the new rule I wondered how much variance is acceptable as many have expressed having equal distribution of lands isn’t where we want to be (agreed) so where is the right balance? /2

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: full disclosure,manaweaving question wasnt hyperbole. I admit that its a waste of time it provides peace of mind. Tilt is real. /1

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: The purpose of the original tweet was to ask a follow up: how much variance do we expect in MTG? MTG isn’t 100% randomness or 100% known information, we expect some variance. So is this mulligan rule a move towards an appropriate amount of variance or is it removing too much?

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: Any amount of shuffling or not shuffling is having an effect on the deck you are presenting. As @clentdc said, When sideboarding do you place the cards on top or bottom and then thoroughly shuffling or are you spacing them out randomly throughout the library before shuffling?

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: Reduce, not remove. How many times have you had an enjoyable game of magic where you or your opponent drew all or no lands/didn't make any relevant plays (without you or them playing chalice).

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: If we're going to say "that's just part of the game, sometimes you get flooded or you get mana screwed" but never in the history of magic has anyone had an enjoyable game of magic drawing all or no lands. SHOULD we seek to eliminate this point of variance or just play hearthstone

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: I hear what you are saying. We also build our decks to reduce variance. This new mulligan rule is rumored to be to reduce variance. Many newer games are removing resources from the deck for the nongames it can lead to. /1

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: Maybe its a peace of mind thing knowing that at least at one point the lands were spread out and if by virtue of randomness lands clump during shuffling then so be it. But being a poor shuffler and getting 75% of the lands on top of the library results in nongames.

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: How many times after playing g1 & you get a mana pocket to start g2. The term mana pocket exists because it happens. To unclump lands thereby reducing that variance & then shuffling sufficiently randomizes while still reducing variance. How many ppl make perfect riffle shuffles?

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: After listening to some pods this week discussing the new rule I wondered how much variance is acceptable as many have expressed having equal distribution of lands isn’t where we want to be (agreed) so where is the right balance? /2

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: full disclosure,manaweaving question wasnt hyperbole. I admit that its a waste of time it provides peace of mind. Tilt is real. /1

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: The purpose of the original tweet was to ask a follow up: how much variance do we expect in MTG? MTG isn’t 100% randomness or 100% known information, we expect some variance. So is this mulligan rule a move towards an appropriate amount of variance or is it removing too much?

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: Any amount of shuffling or not shuffling is having an effect on the deck you are presenting. As @clentdc said, When sideboarding do you place the cards on top or bottom and then thoroughly shuffling or are you spacing them out randomly throughout the library before shuffling?

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: Reduce, not remove. How many times have you had an enjoyable game of magic where you or your opponent drew all or no lands/didn't make any relevant plays (without you or them playing chalice).

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: If we're going to say "that's just part of the game, sometimes you get flooded or you get mana screwed" but never in the history of magic has anyone had an enjoyable game of magic drawing all or no lands. SHOULD we seek to eliminate this point of variance or just play hearthstone

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: I hear what you are saying. We also build our decks to reduce variance. This new mulligan rule is rumored to be to reduce variance. Many newer games are removing resources from the deck for the nongames it can lead to. /1

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: Maybe its a peace of mind thing knowing that at least at one point the lands were spread out and if by virtue of randomness lands clump during shuffling then so be it. But being a poor shuffler and getting 75% of the lands on top of the library results in nongames.

name: Joshua Perschbacher
tweet: How many times after playing g1 & you get a mana pocket to start g2. The term mana pocket exists because it happens. To unclump lands thereby reducing that variance & then shuffling sufficiently randomizes while still reducing variance. How many ppl make perfect riffle shuffles?
